# Browser Automation with agent-browser

Use the `agent-browser` CLI for web automation, testing, and browser interactions.

**IMPORTANT: Always use `--headed` flag when opening browsers so the user can see the browser window.**

## When to Use agent-browser

**Proactively use agent-browser when:**
- User asks you to test a web app or UI
- User is debugging a frontend issue
- User says "check if it works" for a web application
- User mentions localhost, a URL, or a web page
- After making frontend changes, to verify they work
- User asks to fill out forms, click buttons, or navigate pages
- User wants to see what a page looks like or capture screenshots

**Examples of triggers:**
- "Test the login page"
- "Check if the form works"
- "What does the homepage look like?"
- "Debug why the button isn't working"
- "Verify my changes on localhost:3000"
- "Take a screenshot of the dashboard"

## Core Workflow

1. **Navigate**: `agent-browser open <url> --headed` - Open a page (visible browser)
2. **Snapshot**: `agent-browser snapshot -i` - Get interactive elements with refs (@e1, @e2, etc.)
3. **Interact**: Use refs from snapshot to interact:
   - `agent-browser click @e1` - Click element
   - `agent-browser fill @e2 "text"` - Fill input field
   - `agent-browser type @e3 "text"` - Type into element
4. **Re-snapshot**: After page changes, take a new snapshot to get updated refs

## Common Commands

```bash
# Navigation (always use --headed for visible browser)
agent-browser open <url> --headed     # Navigate to URL (visible browser)
agent-browser back                    # Go back
agent-browser forward                 # Go forward
agent-browser reload                  # Reload page

# Interaction (use refs from snapshot)
agent-browser click @e1               # Click element
agent-browser fill @e2 "text"         # Clear and fill input
agent-browser type @e3 "text"         # Type into element (appends)
agent-browser press Enter             # Press key
agent-browser hover @e4               # Hover element
agent-browser select @e5 "option"     # Select dropdown option
agent-browser check @e6               # Check checkbox
agent-browser scroll down 500         # Scroll down 500px

# Get Information
agent-browser snapshot -i             # Interactive elements only (recommended)
agent-browser snapshot                # Full accessibility tree
agent-browser get text @e1            # Get text content
agent-browser get url                 # Get current URL
agent-browser get title               # Get page title
agent-browser screenshot [path]       # Take screenshot

# Wait
agent-browser wait @e1                # Wait for element visible
agent-browser wait 2000               # Wait 2 seconds
agent-browser wait --text "Welcome"   # Wait for text to appear

# State checks
agent-browser is visible @e1          # Check if visible
agent-browser is enabled @e2          # Check if enabled
```

## Snapshot Options

```bash
agent-browser snapshot -i             # Interactive elements only (buttons, inputs, links)
agent-browser snapshot -c             # Compact (remove empty elements)
agent-browser snapshot -d 3           # Limit depth to 3 levels
agent-browser snapshot -i -c          # Combine options
agent-browser snapshot --json         # JSON output for parsing
```

## Sessions (Multiple Browsers)

```bash
agent-browser --session test1 open site-a.com --headed
agent-browser --session test2 open site-b.com --headed
agent-browser session list            # List active sessions
```

## Best Practices

1. Always use `snapshot -i` before interactions to get fresh refs
2. Use refs (@e1, @e2) instead of CSS selectors when possible - they're more reliable
3. Re-snapshot after any action that changes the page
4. Use `--json` flag for machine-readable output
5. Use `agent-browser close` when done to clean up

## Troubleshooting & Testing Workflow

When debugging or testing a web application:

```bash
# 1. Open the app
agent-browser open http://localhost:3000 --headed

# 2. Get current state
agent-browser snapshot -i              # See interactive elements
agent-browser screenshot /tmp/before.png  # Capture current state

# 3. Interact and test
agent-browser fill @e1 "test@example.com"
agent-browser fill @e2 "password123"
agent-browser click @e3                # Click submit button

# 4. Check results
agent-browser wait 2000                # Wait for response
agent-browser snapshot -i              # Check new state
agent-browser screenshot /tmp/after.png   # Capture result
agent-browser get url                  # Did we navigate?

# 5. Check for errors (in browser console)
agent-browser console                  # View console messages
agent-browser errors                   # View JS errors
```

## Debugging Tips

- **Page not loading?** Check `agent-browser get url` and `agent-browser errors`
- **Element not found?** Run `agent-browser snapshot` (without -i) to see full tree
- **Action not working?** Use `agent-browser wait @element` before clicking
- **Need to see what happened?** Take screenshots before/after actions
- **Check network/API calls?** Use `agent-browser console` to see logs
